<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="265">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">Head</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Dorsum of head with indistinct and fine punctures, other parts smooth, with strong luster (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Asicimbex latistriatus Yan &amp; Wei sp. nov., A holotype female in dorsal view B allotype male in dorsal view C head of female in front view D head of male in front view E thoracic notum F head of female in dorsal view G head of male in dorsal view H antenna of female I tibia and tarsus J coxa and femur of male K mesopleuron and metapleuron L gonoforceps M penis valve N lancet O abdominal terga P lateral side of abdomen Q middle serrulae R claw." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.83710.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/707231" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">8C, F</figureCitation>
). Clypeus clearly elevated in middle, anterior margin with small and deep incision; malar space 1.8 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
diameter of middle ocellus (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Asicimbex latistriatus Yan &amp; Wei sp. nov., A holotype female in dorsal view B allotype male in dorsal view C head of female in front view D head of male in front view E thoracic notum F head of female in dorsal view G head of male in dorsal view H antenna of female I tibia and tarsus J coxa and femur of male K mesopleuron and metapleuron L gonoforceps M penis valve N lancet O abdominal terga P lateral side of abdomen Q middle serrulae R claw." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.83710.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/707231" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">8C</figureCitation>
); postocellar area about 1.2-1.3 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
broader than long; median furrow weak, lateral furrows fine, weakly divergent backwards; POL: OOL: OCL = 5: 6: 9; in dorsal view head enlarged behind eye (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Asicimbex latistriatus Yan &amp; Wei sp. nov., A holotype female in dorsal view B allotype male in dorsal view C head of female in front view D head of male in front view E thoracic notum F head of female in dorsal view G head of male in dorsal view H antenna of female I tibia and tarsus J coxa and femur of male K mesopleuron and metapleuron L gonoforceps M penis valve N lancet O abdominal terga P lateral side of abdomen Q middle serrulae R claw." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.83710.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/707231" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">8F</figureCitation>
). Antenna about 1.4 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longer than head breadth (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Asicimbex latistriatus Yan &amp; Wei sp. nov., A holotype female in dorsal view B allotype male in dorsal view C head of female in front view D head of male in front view E thoracic notum F head of female in dorsal view G head of male in dorsal view H antenna of female I tibia and tarsus J coxa and femur of male K mesopleuron and metapleuron L gonoforceps M penis valve N lancet O abdominal terga P lateral side of abdomen Q middle serrulae R claw." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.83710.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/707231" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">8H</figureCitation>
); apical club slightly longer than antennomere 3, with the widest breadth 2.4 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
apical breadth of antennomere 3, antennomere 3 clearly longer than longest axis of eyes (45: 39).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="265">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">Thorax</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Mesothorax densely punctured, punctures on mesoscutellum sparser, surface smooth; mesonotum feebly shiny; punctures on mesepisternum above carina and elevated parts of mesepimeron dense and deep, clearly defined, interspace between punctures smooth, concave area of mesepimeron microsculptured, punctures on ventral side of mesepisternum sparse (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Asicimbex latistriatus Yan &amp; Wei sp. nov., A holotype female in dorsal view B allotype male in dorsal view C head of female in front view D head of male in front view E thoracic notum F head of female in dorsal view G head of male in dorsal view H antenna of female I tibia and tarsus J coxa and femur of male K mesopleuron and metapleuron L gonoforceps M penis valve N lancet O abdominal terga P lateral side of abdomen Q middle serrulae R claw." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.83710.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/707231" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">8E, K</figureCitation>
); mesoscutellum roundly elevated, without middle furrow; oblique middle carina on mesepisternum weak but recognizable; cenchri oval, distance between cenchri about 3.4 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
longest axis of a cenchrus, metascutellum triangularly elevated, distance between serrulae about 2.3 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
basal breadth of a serrula (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Asicimbex latistriatus Yan &amp; Wei sp. nov., A holotype female in dorsal view B allotype male in dorsal view C head of female in front view D head of male in front view E thoracic notum F head of female in dorsal view G head of male in dorsal view H antenna of female I tibia and tarsus J coxa and femur of male K mesopleuron and metapleuron L gonoforceps M penis valve N lancet O abdominal terga P lateral side of abdomen Q middle serrulae R claw." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.83710.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/707231" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">8E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="265">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">Abdomen</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Abdominal tergum 1 with minute punctures and microsculptures, other terga finely and densely microsculptured (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Asicimbex latistriatus Yan &amp; Wei sp. nov., A holotype female in dorsal view B allotype male in dorsal view C head of female in front view D head of male in front view E thoracic notum F head of female in dorsal view G head of male in dorsal view H antenna of female I tibia and tarsus J coxa and femur of male K mesopleuron and metapleuron L gonoforceps M penis valve N lancet O abdominal terga P lateral side of abdomen Q middle serrulae R claw." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.83710.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/707231" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">8O, P</figureCitation>
). Tergum 1 without lateral carina, hind corner roundish, not produced, posterior incision broad and deep, bottom round (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Asicimbex latistriatus Yan &amp; Wei sp. nov., A holotype female in dorsal view B allotype male in dorsal view C head of female in front view D head of male in front view E thoracic notum F head of female in dorsal view G head of male in dorsal view H antenna of female I tibia and tarsus J coxa and femur of male K mesopleuron and metapleuron L gonoforceps M penis valve N lancet O abdominal terga P lateral side of abdomen Q middle serrulae R claw." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.83710.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/707231" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">8O</figureCitation>
); middle process of sternum 7 broad and triangular, basal breadth about 1/3 breadth of sternite 7; lance short and broad, subapical annuli feebly broadened, total length of annuli 3.9 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
height of 13th annulus, first annulus 2.7 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as high as broad (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Asicimbex latistriatus Yan &amp; Wei sp. nov., A holotype female in dorsal view B allotype male in dorsal view C head of female in front view D head of male in front view E thoracic notum F head of female in dorsal view G head of male in dorsal view H antenna of female I tibia and tarsus J coxa and femur of male K mesopleuron and metapleuron L gonoforceps M penis valve N lancet O abdominal terga P lateral side of abdomen Q middle serrulae R claw." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.83710.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/707231" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">8N</figureCitation>
); lancet with 47 annular sutures and 46 serrulae (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Asicimbex latistriatus Yan &amp; Wei sp. nov., A holotype female in dorsal view B allotype male in dorsal view C head of female in front view D head of male in front view E thoracic notum F head of female in dorsal view G head of male in dorsal view H antenna of female I tibia and tarsus J coxa and femur of male K mesopleuron and metapleuron L gonoforceps M penis valve N lancet O abdominal terga P lateral side of abdomen Q middle serrulae R claw." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.83710.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/707231" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">8N</figureCitation>
), middle serrulae narrowly truncate at apex with about 5 proximal and 5 distal subbasal teeth (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Asicimbex latistriatus Yan &amp; Wei sp. nov., A holotype female in dorsal view B allotype male in dorsal view C head of female in front view D head of male in front view E thoracic notum F head of female in dorsal view G head of male in dorsal view H antenna of female I tibia and tarsus J coxa and femur of male K mesopleuron and metapleuron L gonoforceps M penis valve N lancet O abdominal terga P lateral side of abdomen Q middle serrulae R claw." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.83710.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/707231" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">8Q</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="265">
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">Male.</emphasis>
Body length 16 mm (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Asicimbex latistriatus Yan &amp; Wei sp. nov., A holotype female in dorsal view B allotype male in dorsal view C head of female in front view D head of male in front view E thoracic notum F head of female in dorsal view G head of male in dorsal view H antenna of female I tibia and tarsus J coxa and femur of male K mesopleuron and metapleuron L gonoforceps M penis valve N lancet O abdominal terga P lateral side of abdomen Q middle serrulae R claw." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.83710.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/707231" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">8B</figureCitation>
), body color and structure (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Asicimbex latistriatus Yan &amp; Wei sp. nov., A holotype female in dorsal view B allotype male in dorsal view C head of female in front view D head of male in front view E thoracic notum F head of female in dorsal view G head of male in dorsal view H antenna of female I tibia and tarsus J coxa and femur of male K mesopleuron and metapleuron L gonoforceps M penis valve N lancet O abdominal terga P lateral side of abdomen Q middle serrulae R claw." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.83710.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/707231" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">8D, G</figureCitation>
) similar to female except for following parts: posterior of postocellar area in middle with a shallow depressed groove; abdominal terga 2-3 largely blackish brown; middle and hind coxae and femora distinctly elongated, with carina; hind femora distinctly swollen, about twice as broad as trochanter; penis valve shown in Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Asicimbex latistriatus Yan &amp; Wei sp. nov., A holotype female in dorsal view B allotype male in dorsal view C head of female in front view D head of male in front view E thoracic notum F head of female in dorsal view G head of male in dorsal view H antenna of female I tibia and tarsus J coxa and femur of male K mesopleuron and metapleuron L gonoforceps M penis valve N lancet O abdominal terga P lateral side of abdomen Q middle serrulae R claw." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.83710.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/707231" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">8M</figureCitation>
, gonoforceps as shown in Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Asicimbex latistriatus Yan &amp; Wei sp. nov., A holotype female in dorsal view B allotype male in dorsal view C head of female in front view D head of male in front view E thoracic notum F head of female in dorsal view G head of male in dorsal view H antenna of female I tibia and tarsus J coxa and femur of male K mesopleuron and metapleuron L gonoforceps M penis valve N lancet O abdominal terga P lateral side of abdomen Q middle serrulae R claw." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.91.83710.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/707231" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">8L</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="265" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="265">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="265">China (Henan); South Korea?</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="265" type="variation">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="265">Variation.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="265">Body length 13-15 mm in female, 16-17 mm in male; club of antenna dark brown or yellowish brown; middle and hind coxae brown or blackish brown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="265" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="265">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="265">
The specific epithet is a combination of the Latin word: &quot; 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">lati</emphasis>
-&quot; and &quot;- 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">striatus</emphasis>
&quot;, referring to the fore wing with a broad longitudinal smoky stripe.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="265" type="host">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="265">Host plant and larva</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="265">
. The adult types of the new species were reared two years later from the larvae collected on the trunk of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Ulmaceae" genus="Ulmus" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Ulmus" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="265" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">Ulmus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. The matured larvae are yellow colored with black head, thorax and abdomen without black macula.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="265" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="265">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="265">
The senior author of the paper examined 2 females and 3 males of 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. latistriatus" pageId="0" pageNumber="265" rank="species" species="latistriatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">A. latistriatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from South Korea in 2013, when there were only five species (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yan &amp; Yan &amp; Deng &amp; Wei" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Semenov" baseAuthorityYear="1935" family="Cimbicidae" genus="Asicimbex" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Asicimbex eous" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="265" rank="species" species="eous">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">Asicimbex eous</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="comb. nov., New record for China" baseAuthorityName="Gussakovskij" baseAuthorityYear="1947" family="Cimbicidae" genus="Asicimbex" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Asicimbex malaisei" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="265" rank="species" species="malaisei">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">Asicimbex malaisei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yan &amp; Yan &amp; Deng &amp; Wei" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Li &amp; Wu" baseAuthorityYear="2003" family="Cimbicidae" genus="Asicimbex" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Asicimbex elminus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="265" rank="species" species="elminus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">Asicimbex elminus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yan &amp; Yan &amp; Deng &amp; Wei" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Yang" baseAuthorityYear="1996" family="Cimbicidae" genus="Asicimbex" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Asicimbex ulmusvorus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="265" rank="species" species="ulmusvorus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">Asicimbex ulmusvorus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the undescribed 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yan, Deng &amp; Wei" authorityYear="2022" family="Cimbicidae" genus="Asicimbex" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Asicimbex latistriatus" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="265" rank="species" species="latistriatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">Asicimbex latistriatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) of the undescribed genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yan, Deng &amp; Wei" authorityYear="2022" family="Cimbicidae" genus="Asicimbex" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Asicimbex" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="265" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="265">Asicimbex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
known to the author. The specimens were kept in Yeungnam University. Confirmation of this faunal record requires re-examination of the specimens.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
